m iron in the colon","Transport of ferrous iron by DMT1 in the duodenum","Passive diffusion of ferric iron throughout the small intestine","Active transport of transferrin-bound iron in the ileum"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport of ferrous iron by DMT1 in the duodenum\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of dietary iron absorption. Before absorption, dietary ferric iron (Fe3+) is reduced to ferrous iron (Fe2+) by duodenal cytochrome b (Dcytb) at the apical membrane. DMT1 then transports the ferrous iron across the enterocyte membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive diffusion of ferric iron throughout the small intestine\u003C/strong\u003E - Iron requires active transport and must be in ferrous form for absorption\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport of transferrin-bound iron in the ileum\u003C/strong\u003E - Transferrin is involved in blood transport, not intestinal absorption\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitated diffusion of ferric iron in the jejunum\u003C/strong\u003E - Iron must be reduced to ferrous form and requires active transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarrier-mediated uptake of haem iron in the colon\u003C/strong\u003E - Iron absorption occurs primarily in the duodenum and upper jejunum, not the colon\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter absorption, iron is either stored as ferritin or exported via ferroportin into the bloodstream where it binds to transferrin for transport throughout the body.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Iron absorption occurs primarily in the duodenum and upper jejunum through divalent metal transporter 1 (DMT1).","Dietary iron must be reduced from ferric (Fe3+) to ferrous (Fe2+) form by duodenal cytochrome b (Dcytb) before absorption.","F